  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Weaving memory and truth in Guatemala</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project is focused on the fight against impunity and in strengthening groups, spaces and organisations, alliances and coordinations at local, national and international level. The fight against impunity is framed in the pursuit of justice for the survivors of the internal armed conflict, access to justice with equality to be heard and clarify the truth from their experiences and memories. In this way, to guarantee the non-repetition of crimes committed and that these precedents strengthen the justice system, the investigating body of the Public Prosecutor&apos;s Office and build the conditions to address this reality at the level of the whole society. The cases supported are: the Ixil Genocide, Military Zone no. 21 - Creompaz, Josefa and Mar&#xED;a Tiu, Plan de S&#xE1;nchez, among other 22 cases before the Inter-American System. Since the implementation of strategic litigation, the participation of survivors who are at the centre of the justice, truth and memory processes is fundamental, so it is necessary to provide accompaniment to survivors who are involved in legal processes to achieve justice.  The project also aims to strengthen their participation, so that they can seek ways of recovering their political identity, of which they were deprived during the internal armed conflict, and in this way open political spaces and alliances with other organisations and  groups that support collective processes of justice. It also seeks to inform and sensitise society and those unaware of what happened during the internal armed conflict, through production of communication and awareness-raising materials, and activities to publicise these struggles and processes, in order to strengthen the system of Justice and ensure non-repetition. In the same way, women play a fundamental role in justice processes, so it is important to develop a process of recovery of memory with female witnesses and survivors of at least one case of transitional justice,  to strengthen their political participation, recover their identity and highlight their individual and collective history as  women survivors.</narrative>
  </description>
